text: Hypotonia cystinuria syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome and also a type of syndrome, intersecting with entities that have a material basis in some deletion and chromosome. It is defined as a syndrome that arises from a homozygous deletion on chromosome 2p21, affecting the SLC3A1 and PREPL genes. This deletion varies in size between 23.8 to 75.5 kilobases and is characterized by neonatal and infantile hypotonia and failure to thrive, cystinuria type 1 and nephrolithiasis, growth retardation due to growth hormone deficiency, and minor facial dysmorphism. Additionally, hypotonia cystinuria syndrome has an exact synonym: cystinuria with mitochondrial disease.

Salmonellosis, also known as Salmonella infection, is a primary bacterial infectious disease caused by bacteria of the genus Salmonella. It is characterized by symptoms such as abdominal cramps, diarrhea, and vomiting. These symptoms typically appear 12 to 72 hours after infection. In most cases, the illness lasts four to seven days, and most individuals recover without treatment.

Microphthalmia with limb anomalies, which has exact synonyms including MLA, OAS, Waardenburg anophthalmia syndrome, anophthalmia-syndactyly syndrome, and ophthalmoacromelic syndrome, is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, a syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of bilateral or unilateral clinical anophthalmia or microphthalmia and synostosis, syndactyly, oligodactyly, and/or polydactyly. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the SMOC1 gene on chromosome 14q24.

Mal de Meleda is a type of palmoplantar keratosis, which is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of symmetric palmoplantar hyperkeratosis that progressively extends to the dorsal surfaces of hands and feet, along with ichthyotic changes elsewhere. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the SLURP1 gene located on chromosome 8q24. It is also exactly synonymous with Meleda disease, keratosis palmoplantaris transgrediens of Siemens, and transgrediens palmoplantar keratoderma of Siemens.

Patterned macular dystrophy is a type of macular degeneration defined by the abnormal accumulation of lipofuscin in the retinal pigment epithelium, manifesting in distinct patterns such as reticular ('fishnet-like'), macroreticular ('spider-shaped'), and butterfly-shaped. It is also exactly synonymous with patterned dystrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium.

Patterned macular dystrophy 2 is a type of patterned macular dystrophy characterized by a bilateral accumulation of pigmented or yellowish material at the level of the retinal pigment epithelium in lesions that resemble the wings of a butterfly. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CTNNA1 gene on chromosome 5q31. Patterned macular dystrophy 2 is also exactly synonymous with MDPT2 and butterfly-shaped pigmentary macular dystrophy 2.

Patterned macular dystrophy 3 is classified as a type of patterned macular dystrophy. It is defined by a specific pattern of macular dystrophy, characterized as having a 'dry desert land' pattern of the fundus. This condition primarily affects the posterior pole initially and gradually progresses from the temporal fovea to the periphery of the retina, typically developing in the fourth or fifth decade of life. The cause of patterned macular dystrophy 3 is linked to a heterozygous mutation in the MAPKAPK3 gene located on chromosome 3p21. Additionally, patterned macular dystrophy 3 is also known by the exact synonyms MDPT3 and Martinique crinkled retinal pigment epitheliopathy.

Patterned macular dystrophy 1, which is a type of patterned macular dystrophy, is characterized by a bilateral accumulation of pigmented or yellowish material at the level of the retinal pigment epithelium in lesions that resemble the wings of a butterfly. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PRPH2 gene on chromosome 6p21. It is also precisely known as MDPT1 and butterfly-shaped pigmentary macular dystrophy 1.

Macrocephaly autism syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome, which has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by several phenotypes, including macrocephaly, a square face, a long philtrum, frontal bossing, and midface retrusion. The syndrome is defined as a condition characterized by macrocephaly, facial phenotypes such as a square outline with frontal bossing, a 'dished-out' midface, biparietal narrowing, long philtrum, developmental delay, and autism, which arises from a heterozygous mutation in the PTEN gene on chromosome 10q23. Additionally, macrocephaly autism syndrome is exactly synonymous with macrocephaly-intellectual disability-autism syndrome.

Leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter is a type of autosomal recessive disease, leukodystrophy, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This leukodystrophy is characterized by variable neurologic features resulting from a deficiency in astrocyte maturation, including progressive cerebellar ataxia, spasticity, and cognitive impairment associated with white matter lesions on brain imaging, with an onset from early infancy to adulthood. It has exact synonyms including CACH, CACH/VWM, childhood ataxia with central nervous system hypomyelination, and vanishing white matter leukodystrophy. Additionally, it has a related synonym, ovarioleukodystrophy. Furthermore, leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter has narrower matches with ORDO:157713, ORDO:157716, and ORDO:157719, and a related match with ORDO:99853.

Late onset retinal degeneration is a type of retinal degeneration characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of night blindness and drusen deposits, progressing to severe central and peripheral degeneration, with choroidal neovascularization and chorioretinal atrophy with onset in the fifth to sixth decade of life. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the C1QTNF5 gene on chromosome 11q23. Furthermore, late onset retinal degeneration is exactly synonymous with LORD and autosomal dominant late-onset retinal degeneration.

Isolated growth hormone deficiency is a type of hypopituitarism defined by abnormally low levels, absence, or impaired function of growth hormone in the absence of abnormalities in other pituitary hormones. It is exactly synonymous with IGHD, congenital IGHD, congenital isolated GH deficiency, congenital isolated growth hormone deficiency, familial isolated growth hormone deficiency, and non-acquired isolated growth hormone deficiency.

Autosomal dominant keratitis ichthyosis deafness syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease, syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by congenital deafness, keratopachydermia, and constrictions of fingers and toes, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GJB2 gene on chromosome 13q. Additionally, it has the exact synonym "autosomal dominant KID syndrome."

Isolated Growth Hormone Deficiency Type II is a form of isolated growth hormone deficiency. This condition is defined as an isolated growth hormone deficiency that is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. It is characterized by low but detectable levels of GH1, leading to variable degrees of dwarfism. However, these effects are responsive to growth hormone therapy. The condition is caused by dominant negative mutations in the GH1 gene located on chromosome 17q23.3. Isolated Growth Hormone Deficiency Type II is also exactly synonymous with several terms, including IGHD II, Autosomal Dominant Isolated Growth Hormone Deficiency, Autosomal Dominant Pituitary Dwarfism due to Isolated Growth Hormone Deficiency, Congenital IGHD Type II, Congenital Isolated GH Deficiency Type II, and Congenital Isolated Growth Hormone Deficiency Type II.

Isolated Growth Hormone Deficiency Type IA is a type of isolated growth hormone deficiency. This deficiency is characterized by an autosomal recessive inheritance of severe dwarfism, with the onset by 6 months of age, and the variable development of antibodies to growth hormone following exogenous supplementation. This condition has a material basis in null mutations in the GH1 gene on chromosome 17q23.3. It is also known by several exact synonyms including IGHD IA, Illig-type growth hormone deficiency, autosomal recessive isolated growth hormone deficiency, pituitary dwarfism I, primordial dwarfism, and sexual ateleiotic dwarfism.

Isolated growth hormone deficiency type IB is a specific form of isolated growth hormone deficiency. It is defined as an isolated growth hormone deficiency characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, featuring low but detectable levels of growth hormone (GH), short stature, significantly retarded bone age, and a positive response and immunologic tolerance to growth hormone therapy. This condition arises from mutations in the GH1 or GHRHR genes located on chromosomes 17q23.3 and 7p14.3, respectively. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including IGHD IB, congenital IGHD type IB, congenital isolated GH deficiency type IB, congenital isolated growth hormone deficiency type IB, and dwarfism of Sindh. Additionally, it has an exact match with OMIM entry 618157.

Isolated growth hormone deficiency type III is a type of isolated growth hormone deficiency, as well as a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as an isolated growth hormone deficiency marked by dwarfism, variable occurrence of hypogammaglobulinemia, and a generally good response to growth hormone therapy, which stems from a mutation in the BTK gene on chromosome Xq22.1. Isolated growth hormone deficiency type III is also known by several exact synonyms, including Fleisher syndrome, IGHD III, X-linked IGHD, X-linked agammaglobulinemia and isolated growth hormone deficiency, X-linked hypogammaglobulinemia and isolated growth hormone deficiency, X-linked isolated growth hormone deficiency, congenital IGHD type III, congenital isolated GH deficiency type III, congenital isolated growth hormone deficiency type III, and growth hormone deficiency with hypogammaglobulinemia.

Bullous Congenital Ichthyosiform Erythroderma (BCIE) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, ichthyosis, and a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized as an ichthyosis marked by congenital erythema and widespread skin blistering. These blisters evolve into gray hyperkeratoses with a lichenified appearance, a condition that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KRT2 gene located on chromosome 12q13. Furthermore, BCIE is also known by its exact synonyms: bullous type ichthyosis, ichthyosis bullosa of Siemens, and superficial epidermolytic ichthyosis.

Hypoparathyroidism deafness renal disease syndrome, also known exactly as Barakat syndrome, HDR syndrome, and hypoparathyroidism, sensorineural deafness, and renal disease, is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome. It is defined by an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern characterized by hypoparathyroidism, sensorineural deafness, and progressive renal failure. This condition has its material basis in a chromosome deletion that results in haploinsufficiency of the GATA3 gene on chromosome 10p14.

Primary hypomagnesemia is a type of metal metabolism disorder characterized by very low serum magnesium levels, often accompanied by secondary hypocalcemia, with onset typically in the first months of life. It has exact synonyms, including HOMG and primary familial hypomagnesemia.

Renal hypomagnesemia 3 is a specific type of primary hypomagnesemia. It is defined as a hypomagnesemia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance leading to excessive urinary calcium (Ca(2+)) and magnesium (Mg(2+)) excretion. This condition results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CLDN16 gene located on chromosome 3q28. Renal hypomagnesemia 3 is known by several exact synonyms, including FHHNC without severe ocular involvement, HOMG3, familial primary hypomagnesemia with hypercalciuria and nephrocalcinosis without severe ocular involvement, isolated renal hypomagnesemia, primary hypomagnesemia due to a defect in renal tubular transport of magnesium, and renal hypomagnesemia type 3.

Renal hypomagnesemia 5 with ocular involvement is a type of primary hypomagnesemia. It is defined as a hypomagnesemia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of renal magnesium wasting with hypercalcinosis, progressive renal failure, and severe ocular involvement that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the CLDN19 gene on chromosome 1p34.2. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms, including FHHNC with severe ocular involvement, Meier-Blumberg-Imahorn syndrome, bilateral macular coloboma with hypercalciuria, familial hypomagnesemia with hypercalciuria, nephrocalcinosis and severe ocular involvement, and hypercalciuria-bilateral macular coloboma syndrome.

Renal hypomagnesemia 4 is a type of primary hypomagnesemia, which is defined as a hypomagnesemia characterized by isolated hypomagnesemia due to renal loss with normal serum calcium levels and urinary calcium excretion. This condition has a material basis in variation in the chromosome region 4q25. Additionally, renal hypomagnesemia 4 has an exact synonym, HOMG4.

Intestinal hypomagnesemia 1 is a type of primary hypomagnesemia characterized by very low serum magnesium levels due to defects in intestinal absorption and kidney excretion, leading to secondary hypocalcemia. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TRPM6 gene on chromosome 9q21. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including HOMG1, hypomagnesemia caused by selective magnesium malabsorption, hypomagnesemia intestinal type 1, hypomagnesemic tetany, intestinal hypomagnesemia with secondary hypocalcemia, and primary hypomagnesemia with secondary hypocalcemia.

Renal hypomagnesemia 6 is a type of primary hypomagnesemia, which is defined as a hypomagnesemia characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of severely lowered serum magnesium levels without other electrolyte disturbances or abnormalities in urinary magnesium excretion. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CNNM2 gene located on chromosome 10q24. It is also precisely known by its exact synonym, HOMG6.

Renal hypomagnesemia 2 is a type of primary hypomagnesemia and has the definition of a hypomagnesemia characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of hypomagnesemia due to renal magnesium loss that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FXYD2 gene on chromosome 11q23. It also has exact synonyms which include HOMG2 and autosomal dominant primary hypomagnesemia with hypocalciuria.

Osteopathia striata with cranial sclerosis is a type of osteosclerosis characterized by longitudinal striations of the metaphyses of the long bones, sclerosis of the craniofacial bones, macrocephaly, cleft palate, and hearing loss in females, with fetal or neonatal lethality in males. This condition has a material basis in mutation in the AMER1 gene on chromosome Xq11. Furthermore, osteopathia striata with cranial sclerosis is exactly synonymous with Robinow-Unger syndrome and hyperostosis generalisata with striations.

Ossification of the posterior longitudinal ligament of the spine is a type of connective tissue disease and also falls under the category of diseases that occur in some ligament of the vertebral column. It is defined as a connective tissue disease characterized by ectopic ossification of the posterior longitudinal spinal ligament, which results in spinal cord compression, myelopathy, and hyperreflexia. Additionally, it has the exact synonym OPLL.

Transient myeloproliferative syndrome is a type of myeloproliferative neoplasm, which is characterized by leukocytosis in newborns with Down syndrome. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms including MST, TAM, transient abnormal myelopoiesis, transient leukemia, transient leukemia of Down syndrome, and transient myeloproliferative disease.

Prune belly syndrome, also known precisely as Eagle-Barret syndrome, Obrisnksy syndrome, or abdominal muscle deficiency syndrome, is a type of syndrome and a specific autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a constellation of symptoms, including megacystis with disorganized detrusor muscle, cryptorchidism, and thin abdominal musculature with overlying lax skin. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the CHRM3 gene located on chromosome 1q43, indicating its autosomal recessive inheritance.

Ectopic Cushing syndrome is a type of primary hyperaldosteronism characterized by a tumor outside the pituitary gland that produces adrenocorticotropic hormone. It is also known by its exact synonyms "Cushing syndrome due to ectopic ACTH secretion" and "ectopic ACTH secreting tumor."

Parkinson's disease 19A is characterized as a type of autosomal recessive disease and early onset Parkinson's disease, which fundamentally arises from some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as an early-onset Parkinson's disease that originates from a homozygous mutation in the DNAJC6 gene located on chromosome 1p31. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with juvenile onset Parkinson disease 19A and juvenile onset Parkinson's disease 19A, indicating both terms precisely identify this condition.

Late-onset Parkinson's disease is a type of Parkinson's disease characterized by the onset of motor symptoms typically after 60 years of age. It is also precisely referred to as late-onset Parkinson disease.

Juvenile onset Parkinson's disease is a type of early-onset Parkinson's disease and is also a type of condition that begins during young adulthood. It is defined as an early-onset Parkinson's disease characterized by the onset of motor symptoms prior to 21 years of age. Additionally, it has an exact synonym, which is juvenile-onset Parkinson disease.

Early onset Parkinson's disease is a type of Parkinson's disease characterized by the onset of motor symptoms earlier than typically seen, usually prior to 50 years of age. It also has the exact synonym "early-onset Parkinson disease."

Parkinson's disease 4 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and is also a type of late-onset Parkinson's disease, which is something that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is specifically defined as a late-onset Parkinson disease that has its material basis in the heterozygous triplication of the alpha-synuclein gene on chromosome 4q22. Furthermore, Parkinson's disease 4 is exactly synonymous with autosomal dominant Lewy body Parkinson disease 4, autosomal dominant Parkinson disease 4, and autosomal dominant Parkinson's disease 4.

Parkinson's disease 23 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and an early-onset Parkinson's disease, indicating that it has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is an early-onset Parkinson disease that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the VPS13C gene located on chromosome 15q22. Furthermore, Parkinson's disease 23 is exactly synonymous with autosomal recessive early-onset Parkinson disease 23, also referred to as autosomal recessive early-onset Parkinson's disease 23.

Parkinson's disease 17 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a subtype of late-onset Parkinson's disease, characterized specifically as something that fundamentally involves autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a late-onset Parkinson's disease that results from a heterozygous mutation in the VPS35 gene located on chromosome 16q13. Additionally, it is precisely referred to by two exact synonyms: Parkinson disease 17 and autosomal dominant Parkinson disease 17.

Parkinson's disease 20 is characterized as a type of autosomal recessive disease and is a form of early-onset Parkinson's disease. It is specifically associated with a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of Parkinson's disease 20 highlights that it is an early-onset Parkinson disease which originates from a homozygous mutation in the SYNJ1 gene located on chromosome 21q22. Furthermore, it is precisely referred to as early-onset Parkinson disease 20 and early-onset Parkinson's disease 20, serving as exact synonyms for this condition.

Parkinson's disease 14 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of late-onset Parkinson's disease that essentially has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific condition is defined as a late-onset Parkinson disease characterized by a homozygous mutation in the PLA2G6 gene located on chromosome 22q13. Furthermore, Parkinson's disease 14 is exactly synonymous with Dystonia-Parkinsonism Adult-Onset, autosomal recessive Parkinson disease 14, and autosomal recessive Parkinson's disease 14.

Lymphoplasmacytic lymphoma is a type of B-cell lymphoma, characterized by the accumulation of monoclonal cells in the bone marrow and peripheral lymphoid tissues, and associated with the production of serum immunoglobulin M (IgM) monoclonal protein. It is exactly synonymous with Waldenstroem's macroglobulinemia, Waldenstrom Macroglobulinemia, and lymphoplasmacytic lymphoma with IgM gammopathy. Furthermore, lymphoplasmacytic lymphoma has an exact match with MESH:D008258.

Norman Roberts syndrome is a type of lissencephaly and also a type of autosomal recessive disease, which essentially has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific lissencephaly, known as Norman Roberts syndrome, is defined by having its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the gene encoding reelin (RELN) on chromosome 7q22. It has exact synonyms: lissencephaly 2 and lissencephaly syndrome, Norman-Roberts type.
Thrombosis is a type of vascular disease defined as a vascular disease caused by the formation of a blood clot inside a blood vessel, which obstructs the flow of blood through the circulatory system.

Legume allergy is a type of fruit allergy and can also be classified as a type of allergy that is triggered by at least some legume food products. It is defined as a fruit allergy triggered by Fabaceae (legume) plant fruit or seed food products. Moreover, legume allergy is also exactly synonymous with Fabaceae allergy.

Karyomegalic interstitial nephritis (KIN), also known exactly as KMIN, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and interstitial nephritis. It is characterized by nephritis, interstitial fibrosis, and enlarged and atypical tubular epithelial cell nuclei, which is based on homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FAN1 gene on chromosome 15q13.3. This condition is also a type of disorder that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Craniosynostosis 7, which has the exact synonym CRS7, is a type of digenic disease and a specific form of craniosynostosis. This condition involves a skull deformity characterized by the skull's inability to accommodate the growing brain, primarily due to a weakly penetrant heterozygous mutation in the SMAD6 gene located on chromosome 15q22. This is typically accompanied by the risk allele of a common variant near the BMP2 gene on chromosome 20p12, which can lead to potential elevation in intracranial pressure. Additionally, craniosynostosis 7 is classified as a condition that, at a minimum, has a material basis in digenic inheritance.

Proteosome associated autoinflammatory syndrome is a type of syndrome that is defined by its characteristics of early onset, dermatitis, immune response dysregulation, and variable features including recurrent fever, joint contractures, lipodystrophy, hepatosplenomegaly, anemia, and calcifications.

Proteasome Associated Autoinflammatory Syndrome 2 (PRAAS2) is a form of proteasome associated autoinflammatory syndrome, which falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. It is specifically characterized as a type of condition that has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of PRAAS2 highlights it as a proteasome-associated autoinflammatory syndrome distinguished by severe inflammatory neutrophilic dermatitis, autoimmunity, and variable immunodeficiency. This condition is caused by heterozygous mutations in the POMP gene located on chromosome 13q12.

Proteasome-associated autoinflammatory syndrome 4 (PRAAS4) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the broader category of proteasome-associated autoinflammatory syndromes. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, PRAAS4 is defined by its onset of panniculitis and erythematous skin lesions in early infancy, accompanied by variable features such as lymphadenopathy, myositis, delayed motor and speech development, and autoimmune features. This condition has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the PSMG2 gene located on chromosome 18p11.

Proteasome Associated Autoinflammatory Syndrome 3 (PRAAS3) is categorized as a type of autosomal recessive disease, proteasome associated autoinflammatory syndrome, and digenic disease. It is defined by its manifestation, which includes nodular dermatitis, recurrent fever, myositis, panniculitis-induced lipodystrophy, lymphadenopathy, and dysregulation of the immune response, notably associated with an abnormal type I interferon-induced gene expression pattern starting in early infancy. The material basis for this syndrome lies in either a homozygous mutation in the PSMB4 gene on chromosome 1q21 or a combination of a heterozygous mutation in the PSMB4 gene and a heterozygous mutation in the PSMB9 gene on chromosome 6p21. This indicates that its genetic foundation includes elements of both autosomal recessive and digenic inheritance patterns.

Facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy 3 (FSHD3), also known as facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy type 3, is a specific type of facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy and a form of digenic disease. It is characterized by a type of condition that fundamentally has a material basis in digenic inheritance. Specifically, FSHD3 is defined as a facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy that manifests with adult onset of proximal muscle weakness affecting the face, neck, scapular muscles, and upper and lower limbs. This condition has its material basis in the combination of a homozygous mutation in the LRIF1 gene located on chromosome 1p13 and the presence of a haplotype on chromosome 4 that allows for DUX4 expression.

Facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy 4 is a type of facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy and a digenic disease. It is also characterized as a condition that at least has a material basis in some digenic inheritance. Specifically, facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy 4 is defined as a facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy characterized by adult onset of progressive muscle weakness of the face and upper extremity muscles with disease progression that has a material basis in the combination of a heterozygous mutation in the DNMT3B gene on chromosome 20q11 and the presence of a haplotype on chromosome 4 that is permissive for DUX4 expression. Additionally, facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy 4 has exact synonyms, which are FSHD4 and facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy type 4.

Proteasome associated autoinflammatory syndrome 5 (PRAAS5) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also a subset of proteasome associated autoinflammatory syndromes. It has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The syndrome is defined by a proteasome-associated autoinflammatory condition characterized by recurrent, polymorphic disseminated cutaneous rash with annular lesions, non-specific lymphocytic infiltration, fever, failure to thrive, persistent hepatosplenomegaly, emaciated face, long slender fingers, elevated acute-phase reactants, and microcytic anemia. This condition is caused by a homozygous mutation in the PSMB10 gene on chromosome 16q22.

Otosclerosis 1 is a type of otosclerosis and also a type of condition that has its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an otosclerosis characterized by isolated endochondral bone sclerosis of the labyrinthine capsule, which has its material basis in the locus associated with the otosclerosis-1 gene (OTSC1) on chromosome 15q26.1. Additionally, Otosclerosis 1 has the exact synonym OTSC1.

Otosclerosis 2 is a type of otosclerosis and also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an otosclerosis that has its material basis in the locus associated with the otosclerosis-2 gene (OTSC2) on chromosome 7q. Additionally, otosclerosis 2 has an exact synonym, OTSC2.

Otosclerosis 3 is a type of otosclerosis and also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an otosclerosis that has its material basis in the locus associated with the otosclerosis-3 gene (OTSC3) on chromosome 6p. Additionally, otosclerosis 3 has the exact synonym OTSC3.

Otosclerosis 4 is a type of otosclerosis and also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an otosclerosis that has its material basis in the locus associated with the otosclerosis-4 gene (OTSC4) on chromosome 16q loci. Additionally, otosclerosis 4 has an exact synonym, OTSC4.

Otosclerosis 5 is a type of otosclerosis and also known by its exact synonym OTSC5. It is characterized by conductive hearing impairment and has its material basis in the locus associated with the otosclerosis-5 gene (OTSC5) on loci 3q22-q24. Additionally, otosclerosis 5 is a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.

Otosclerosis 7 is a type of otosclerosis and also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an otosclerosis that has its material basis in the locus associated with the otosclerosis-7 gene (OTSC7) on chromosome 6q13 loci. Moreover, Otosclerosis 7 has an exact synonym, OTSC7.

Otosclerosis 8 is a type of otosclerosis and also a type of condition that has at least a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an otosclerosis that has its material basis in the locus associated with the otosclerosis-8 gene (OTSC8) on loci chromosome 9p13.1-q21.11. Moreover, otosclerosis 8 has an exact synonym, OTSC8.

Otosclerosis 10 is a type of otosclerosis and also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an otosclerosis that has its material basis in the locus associated with the otosclerosis-10 gene (OTSC10) on chromosome loci 1q41-q44. Additionally, otosclerosis 10 has the exact synonym OTSC10.

Otosclerosis 11 is a type of otosclerosis and is also known by the exact synonym OTSC11. It is characterized by a type of otosclerosis that manifests as progressive hearing loss starting in the second to third decade of life. This condition has a material basis in the locus associated with the Forkhead Box L1 gene (FOXL1) on chromosome 16q24. Additionally, otosclerosis 11 is a condition that, at a minimum, involves autosomal dominant inheritance.

Non-syndromic X-linked intellectual developmental disorder 111 is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, which is characterized by different degrees of impaired intellectual development associated with motor, speech, and behavioral impairments. This condition has a material basis in hemizygous or heterozygous mutation in the SLITRK2 gene on chromosome Xq27. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with XLID111.

Developmental dysplasia of the hip is a type of bone development disease that affects the hip. It is characterized by an abnormality of the seating of the femoral head in the acetabulum, indicating its specific location and nature within bone development diseases.

Developmental dysplasia of the hip 1 (DDH1) is a type of developmental dysplasia of the hip and an autosomal dominant disease, which specifically indicates that it at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by a developmental dysplasia of the hip that features a shallow hip socket. This condition has its material basis in variation in the chromosomal region 13q22.

Developmental Dysplasia of the Hip 2 (DDH2) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which specifically falls under the broader category of developmental dysplasia of the hip. It is a condition that arises from autosomal dominant inheritance with a material basis in variation found in the chromosomal region 3p22.2. DDH2 is characterized by incomplete formation of the acetabulum leading to dislocation of the femur, suboptimal joint function, and accelerated wear of the articular cartilage, which eventually results in arthritis.

Developmental delay, dysmorphic facies, and brain anomalies is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder, which is defined as an autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder characterized by global developmental delay with impaired intellectual development, speech delay, nonspecific dysmorphic facial features, hypotonia, and impaired overall growth with small head circumference. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the U2AF2 gene on chromosome 19q13. Additionally, it has the exact synonym DEVDFB.

Neurodevelopmental disorder with microcephaly, epilepsy, and brain atrophy is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder and has the exact synonym NEDMEBA. It is characterized by a global developmental delay, severe intellectual disability with poor or absent speech and autistic stereotypic behaviors, microcephaly, early-onset generalized seizures, and hypotonia. The disorder has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the TRAPPC6B gene on chromosome 14q21.

Infantile hypotonia with psychomotor retardation and characteristic facies 3 is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder, which at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This disorder is defined as an autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder characterized by very poor,if any, psychomotor development, poor speech, inability to walk independently, and onset at birth or in early infancy. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TBCK gene on chromosome 4q24. This condition is also exactly synonymous with HYPOTONIA, INFANTILE, WITH PSYCHOMOTOR RETARDATION AND CHARACTERISTIC FACIES 3, IHPRF3, and TBCK-related intellectual disability syndrome.

3 Methylglutaconic aciduria type 8 is a specific form of 3 methylglutaconic aciduria and an autosomal recessive disease that fundamentally arises from some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a 3-methylglutaconic aciduria that originates from a homozygous mutation in the HTRA2 gene located on chromosome 2p13. This condition is also exactly known as 3-methylglutaconic aciduria type VIII or MGCA8.

3-Methylglutaconic aciduria type 9 is a type of 3-methylglutaconic aciduria and an autosomal recessive disease. It specifically arises from a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined by a 3-methylglutaconic aciduria that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the TIMM50 gene on chromosome 19q13. It is also exactly synonymous with 3-methylglutaconic acuduria type IX, MGCA9.

Blastoma is defined as a cell type cancer that has its material basis in abnormally proliferating cells which derive from precursor cells known as blast cells. It is considered the same as something that intersects with something that is cancer and something that at least derives from some non-terminally differentiated cell. Moreover, blastoma is identified as a type of cell type cancer.

Myeloid neoplasm is a type of bone marrow cancer, defined as a bone marrow cancer formed of any one of the bone marrow cells belonging to the granulocytic (neutrophil, eosinophil, basophil), monocytic/macrophage, erythroid, megakaryocytic, and mast cell lineages.

Y linked spermatogenic failure 2 is a type of Y linked monogenic disease, spermatogenic failure, and something that at least has a material basis in some Y linked inheritance. Spermatogenic failure 1 is a type of spermatogenic failure that is defined as a spermatogenic failure characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of spermatogenic failure resulting from meiotic defects. X-linked spermatogenic failure 1 is a type of Sertoli cell-only syndrome and has the definition: A Sertoli cell-only syndrome characterized by X-linked inheritance. It also has the exact synonym SPGFX1.

Autosomal recessive chronic granulomatous disease 2 (ARCGD2) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, chronic granulomatous disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Autosomal recessive chronic granulomatous disease 1 is classified under several categories: it is a type of autosomal recessive disease, a type of chronic granulomatous disease, and a type that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Autosomal recessive chronic granulomatous disease 4 is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the broader category of chronic granulomatous diseases. Autosomal recessive chronic granulomatous disease 3 is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is an autosomal recessive disease, a chronic granulomatous disease, and is classified as something that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This disease is also known by several exact synonyms: CDG3, autosomal recessive chronic granulomatous disease cytochrome b-positive type III, autosomal recessive cytochrome b-positive CGD type III, and chronic granulomatous disease due to NCF4 deficiency.

X-linked chronic granulomatous disease (XCGD) is a type of chronic granulomatous disease and falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases. It is characterized by a specific inheritance pattern that has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. The disease is defined by its X-linked inheritance pattern and results from mutations in the CYBB gene located on chromosome Xp21.1-p11.4. Infantile onset distal myopathy is a type of distal myopathy and a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by having at least a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and its existence begins during an infantile onset. The disease is defined as a distal myopathy characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance, infantile onset, and progressive disease development.

Distal myopathy 1, which is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of distal myopathy, is characterized by a specific autosomal dominant inheritance pattern. This condition is defined as a distal myopathy characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance with a material basis in mutation in the MYH7 gene on chromosome 14q11.2. It is also known by several exact synonyms including Distal myopathy type 1, Gowers disease, Laing distal myopathy, Laing early-onset distal myopathy, and MPD1.

Miyoshi muscular dystrophy, also known precisely as Miyoshi myopathy, is a type of distal myopathy and falls under the category of conditions that, at a minimum, manifest muscle weakness as a symptom. It is defined as a distal myopathy characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, featuring distal muscle weakness in the upper and lower limbs that spares the intrinsic muscles of the hands, with onset typically occurring in young adulthood.

Miyoshi Muscular Dystrophy 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the broader category of Miyoshi Muscular Dystrophy. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this form of Miyoshi Muscular Dystrophy, known as Miyoshi Muscular Dystrophy 1, is defined by a mutation in the DYSF gene located on chromosome 2p13. Miyoshi muscular dystrophy 2 is a type of Miyoshi muscular dystrophy and also falls under the category of conditions that at least have the symptom of some muscle weakness. Miyoshi Muscular Dystrophy 3 (MMD3), which has exact synonyms including MMD3 and Miyoshi Myopathy 3, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of Miyoshi Muscular Dystrophy. Familial Partial Lipodystrophy Type 2 is a specific kind of familial partial lipodystrophy, which also falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. This condition is characterized by an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern, with its material basis linked to autosomal dominant inheritance. Familial partial lipodystrophy type 5 is a type of familial partial lipodystrophy and an autosomal recessive disease, characterized by a specific autosomal recessive inheritance. Familial partial lipodystrophy type 3 (FPLD3) is a subtype of familial partial lipodystrophy, which is a type of autosomal dominant disease. Familial partial lipodystrophy type 4 (FPLD4) is a type of familial partial lipodystrophy and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a specific autosomal dominant inheritance pattern, with a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Familial Partial Lipodystrophy Type 6 (FPLD6) is a type of familial partial lipodystrophy and an autosomal recessive disease. Hereditary lymphedema IC is a type of hereditary lymphedema and falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. Hereditary lymphedema IA is a type of hereditary lymphedema and an autosomal dominant disease, which means it at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Hereditary lymphedema II, a type of hereditary lymphedema, is also classified as an autosomal dominant disease and is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Familial hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia 7 (FH7) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that falls under the category of hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia. This condition is characterized by an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern and is associated with abnormal blood glucose concentrations. FH7 is specifically defined as a hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of postexercise hypoglycemia with marked hyperinsulinism, which is caused by a mutation in the SLC16A1 gene located on chromosome 1p13.2. Familial Hyperinsulinemic Hypoglycemia 4 (HHF4) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia, which is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and exhibits a phenotype of abnormal blood glucose concentration. It is specifically defined as a hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia characterized by an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern with seizures, which has a material basis in a mutation in the HADH gene on chromosome 4q25. Furthermore, HHF4 is also known by several exact synonyms including hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia due to short chain 3-hydroxylacyl-CoA dehydrogenase deficiency, hyperinsulinism due to SCHAD deficiency, hyperinsulinism due to glutamodehydrogenase deficiency, and hyperinsulinism due to short chain 3-hydroxylacyl-CoA dehydrogenase deficiency, highlighting the various underlying causes associated with this condition.

Familial hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia 3 is a specific type of autosomal dominant disease, which falls under the broader category of hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia. It is characterized by a particular type of condition that essentially requires an autosomal dominant inheritance for its material basis and is associated with an abnormal blood glucose concentration phenotype. Familial hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia 6 (HHF6), also known exactly as HI/HA syndrome or hyperinsulinism-hyperammonemia syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia. The condition is defined as a hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of excessive insulin secretion, asymptomatic hyperammonemia, and episodes of hypoglycemia induced by fasting or protein-rich meals, which has its material basis in a mutation in the GLUD1 gene on chromosome 10q23.3.

Familial hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia 2 is a type of hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia, which is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of severe hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia that is resistant to diazoxide treatment. Familial hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia 1 (HHF1) is a type of condition that encompasses various forms of inheritance and characteristics. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and demonstrates a phenotype of abnormal blood glucose concentration. Progressive familial intrahepatic cholestasis is a type of intrahepatic cholestasis and it is defined as an intrahepatic cholestasis characterized by early onset of chronic unremitting cholestasis of hepatocellular origin that progresses to hepatic fibrosis, cirrhosis, and end-stage liver disease before adulthood. CDG I IA is also known by several exact synonyms, including Alkuraya Syndrome, CDG IIa, CDG2A, CDGIIa, CDGS2, Carbohydrate-Deficient Glycoprotein Syndrome, Type II, Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation, Type IIa, and is described to manifest features such as mental retardation, growth retardation, a prominent columella, and an open mouth.

Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type I Ib (CDG IIb) is classified under several categories: it is a type of Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type II, an Autosomal Recessive Disease, and is also characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, CDG IId is exactly synonymous with CDG2D and CDGIId, indicating that these terms refer to the same medical condition.

The congenital disorder of glycosylation type I IE is known by several exact synonyms, including CDG IIe, CDG syndrome type IIe, CDG2E, CDGIIde, COG7-CDG, and Carbohydrate deficient glycoprotein syndrome type IIe.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation type I IK is a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation type II, and it is also classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease. Congenital disorder of glycosylation type I IL is a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation type II and is also categorized as a type of autosomal recessive disease. Additionally, congenital disorder of glycosylation type I IL is known by several exact synonyms including CDG IIl, CDG syndrome type IIL, CDG2L, CDGIIdl, and COG6-CGD, as well as Congenital disorder of glycosylation type 2l.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation type I IM is categorized under several types: it is a form of congenital disorder of glycosylation type II, an X-linked dominant disease, and it pertains to conditions with a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance. Furthermore, it is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. The disorder is defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation type II characterized by infantile onset seizures, hypsarrhythmia, hypotonia, and severe intellectual disability with lack of speech. In addition to its primary designation, congenital disorder of glycosylation type I IM is also known by several exact synonyms: SLC35A2-CDG, congenital disorder of glycosylation type 2m, developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 22, and epileptic encephalopathy, early infantile, 22.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation type I IQ is classified as a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation type II, and it also falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. Hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer type 8 (HNPCC8) is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome and Lynch syndrome. It falls within the intersection of conditions that have a material basis in some form of deletion and chromosome-related issues. Specifically, HNPCC8 is defined as a Lynch syndrome characterized by a heterozygous deletion of the 3' part of the EPCAM gene and intergenic regions adjacent to the MSH2 gene on chromosome 2p21. This genetic alteration leads to transcriptional read-through and subsequent silencing of MSH2 in tissues that express EPCAM.

Lynch Syndrome 1 is a type of Lynch Syndrome and is also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Lynch Syndrome that has its material basis in heterozygous mutations in the MSH2 gene on chromosome 2p21-p16. Lynch Syndrome 1 is precisely known as FCC1, HNPCC1, familial nonpolyposis colon cancer type 1, and hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer type 1.

Hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer type 5 (HNPCC5) is a type of Lynch syndrome and is also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Lynch syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the MSH6 gene on chromosome 2p16.

Hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer type 6 is a type of Lynch syndrome and has an exact synonym, HNPCC6. It is defined as a Lynch syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TGFBR2 gene located on chromosome 3p22.

Hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer type 2 is a type of Lynch syndrome, which is defined by its material basis in mutations in the MLH1 gene located on chromosome 3p22.2. This condition is exactly synonymous with several other terms including COCA2, FCC2, HNPCC2, and familial nonpolyposis colon cancer type 2, indicating the various ways it is identified and referred to in the medical community.

Hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer type 4 is a type of Lynch syndrome and has an exact synonym, HNPCC4. It is defined as a Lynch syndrome that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PMS2 gene on chromosome 7p22.

Hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer type 7 is a type of Lynch syndrome and has an exact synonym, HNPCC7. It is defined as a Lynch syndrome that has its material basis in mutation in the MLH3 gene on chromosome 14q24.3.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 15 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly characterized by impaired intellectual development with poor speech, progressive microcephaly, and appendicular spasticity, which stems from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MFSD2A gene on chromosome 1p34. It is precisely known by the synonyms MCPH15, NEDMISBA, and neurodevelopmental disorder with progressive microcephaly, spasticity, and brain imaging abnormalities.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 7 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly and has the exact synonym MCPH7. It is defined as a primary autosomal recessive microcephaly that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the STIL gene on chromosome 1p33.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 14 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly and has an exact synonym MCPH14. It is defined as a primary autosomal recessive microcephaly that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SASS6 gene on chromosome 1p21.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 5 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly, which is defined as a primary autosomal recessive microcephaly that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ASPM gene on chromosome 1q31. Additionally, it has the exact synonym MCPH5.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 19 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly and has the exact synonym MCPH19. It is defined as a primary autosomal recessive microcephaly that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the COPB2 gene on chromosome 3q23.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 8 (MCPH8) is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly. It is defined as a primary autosomal recessive microcephaly that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CEP135 gene on chromosome 4q.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 13 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly. It is defined as a primary autosomal recessive microcephaly that is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CENPE gene located on chromosome 4q24. Additionally, it is precisely synonymous with MCPH13.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 12 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly and has the exact synonym MCPH12. It is defined as a primary autosomal recessive microcephaly that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CDK6 gene on chromosome 7q21.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 1 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly, and it is precisely defined as a primary autosomal recessive microcephaly that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MCPH1 gene on chromosome 8p23. Additionally, primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 1 is exactly synonymous with MCPH1.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 3 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly and has an exact synonym, MCPH3. It is defined as a primary autosomal recessive microcephaly that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CDK5RAP2 gene on chromosome 9q33.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 11 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly, which is defined as a primary autosomal recessive microcephaly that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PHC1 gene on chromosome 12p13. Additionally, primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 11 is exactly synonymous with MCPH11.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 17 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly and has an exact synonym, MCPH17. It is defined as a primary autosomal recessive microcephaly that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CIT gene on chromosome 12q24.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 16 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly, which is defined as a primary autosomal recessive microcephaly that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ANKLE2 gene on chromosome 12q24. Additionally, it has the exact synonym MCPH16.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 6 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly and is exactly synonymous with MCPH6. Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 4 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly and has an exact synonym, MCPH4.
