Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 9 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly and has an exact synonym, MCPH9. It is defined as a primary autosomal recessive microcephaly that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CEP152 gene on chromosome 15q21.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 2 with or without cortical malformations is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly, and it is defined as a primary autosomal recessive microcephaly that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the WDR62 gene on chromosome 19q13. Furthermore, it has the exact synonym MCPH2.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 10 is a type of primary autosomal recessive microcephaly, and it is precisely defined as a primary autosomal recessive microcephaly that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ZNF335 gene on chromosome 20q13. Furthermore, primary autosomal recessive microcephaly 10 has an exact synonym, MCPH10.

Primary autosomal dominant microcephaly 18 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, primary microcephaly, and is something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a primary microcephaly that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the WDFY3 gene on chromosome 4q21. Moreover, it has the exact synonym MCPH18.

Primary autosomal recessive microcephaly is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of primary microcephaly. It is also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by microcephaly present at birth, wherein the brain is small but has normal architecture, and is accompanied by nonprogressive mental retardation that has a material basis in an autosomal recessive mutation. This condition has the exact synonym MCPH.

Primary microcephaly is a type of microcephaly characterized by the condition being present at birth, where the brain is small but has normal architecture, and includes nonprogressive mental retardation. It is also exactly synonymous with true microcephaly.

Multiple epiphyseal dysplasia 2 (MED2) is an autosomal dominant disease and a specific type of multiple epiphyseal dysplasia caused by a collagen 9 anomaly. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. MED2 is defined as a multiple epiphyseal dysplasia due to a collagen 9 anomaly, which results from a heterozygous mutation in the COL9A2 gene located on chromosome 1p34. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with EDM2.

Multiple epiphyseal dysplasia 5 (MED5) is recognized as a type of autosomal dominant disease and falls under the broader category of multiple epiphyseal dysplasia. It is characterized by its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, MED5 is defined by a heterozygous mutation in the MATN3 gene located on chromosome 2p24. In terms of nomenclature, MED5 is precisely known by several exact synonyms including BHMED (Bilateral Hereditary Microepiphyseal Dysplasia), EDM5, and Multiple Epiphyseal Dysplasia MATN3-related, highlighting its diverse but specific identification within the medical community.

Multiple Epiphyseal Dysplasia 4 (MED4), also known precisely as EDM4, Polyepiphyseal Dysplasia Type 4, multiple epiphyseal dysplasia with bilateral patellae, multiple epiphyseal dysplasia with clubfoot, and rMED, is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease. It falls under the broader category of multiple epiphyseal dysplasia and is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. MED4 is defined by a homozygous mutation in the SLC26A2 gene located on chromosome 5q32, making it a distinct form of the condition with a genetic basis.

Multiple epiphyseal dysplasia 6 (MED6), which is also precisely known as EDM6, is identified as an autosomal dominant disease. This type of multiple epiphyseal dysplasia stems from a collagen 9 anomaly and inherently possesses a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, MED6 is defined as a multiple epiphyseal dysplasia due to a collagen 9 anomaly, which results from a heterozygous mutation in the COL9A1 gene located on chromosome 6p13.

Multiple epiphyseal dysplasia 7 (MED7), which has the exact synonym EDM7, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the broader category of multiple epiphyseal dysplasia. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically through a homozygous mutation in the CANT1 gene located on chromosome 17q25.

Multiple epiphyseal dysplasia 1 is a specific type of multiple epiphyseal dysplasia and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this form of multiple epiphyseal dysplasia, also known as EDM1, MED1, multiple epiphyseal dysplasia COMP-related, or polyepiphyseal dysplasia type 1, is defined by a heterozygous mutation in the COMP gene located on chromosome 19p13.

Multiple epiphyseal dysplasia 3 (MED3), which has the exact synonyms EDM3 and multiple epiphyseal dysplasia 3 with or without myopathy, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of multiple epiphyseal dysplasia caused by a collagen 9 anomaly. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, MED3 is defined as a multiple epiphyseal dysplasia due to a collagen 9 anomaly that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the COL9A3 gene located on chromosome 20q13.

Multiple epiphyseal dysplasia due to collagen 9 anomaly is a specific type of multiple epiphyseal dysplasia and is classified as a monogenic disease, indicating it has a basis in gene mutations. Specifically, it is defined as a multiple epiphyseal dysplasia that arises from mutations in any of the members of the COL9A gene family, which includes COL9A1, COL9A2, and COL9A3. This condition exemplifies a disease with a genetic foundation.

Post cardiac arrest syndrome is a type of syndrome that is characterized by four main components: post-cardiac arrest brain injury, post-cardiac arrest myocardial dysfunction, systemic ischemia reperfusion response, and persistent precipitating pathologies. It also has the exact synonym "post cardiac syndrome."

Craniolenticulosutural dysplasia is a type of autosomal recessive disease, syndrome, and something that has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome in neonates characterized by facial dysmorphism, late-closing fontanels, cataract, and skeletal defects. The syndrome has its material basis in the mutation of the SEC23A gene on the 14th chromosome, leading to underproduction in the collagen secreting pathway and distension of the endoplasmic reticulum, which results in bone defects. Additionally, craniolenticulosutural dysplasia is exactly synonymous with Boyadjiev-Jabs Syndrome and cranio-lenticulo-sutural dysplasia, CLSD.

Rippling muscle disease 1 is a type of muscle tissue disease that also qualifies as a condition where at least muscle pain is a symptom. It is defined as a muscle tissue disease characterized by electrically silent contractions of the skeletal muscles in response to mechanical stimuli. This disease has a material basis in mutations in a gene localized to 1q41 at the distal end of the long arm of chromosome 1. Additionally, rippling muscle disease 1 is associated with symptoms including a characteristic lateral rolling movement of muscle, muscle cramps, muscle pain, and muscle stiffness during or following exercise.

Absence epilepsy is a type of electroclinical syndrome that is defined as an electroclinical syndrome characterized by the occurrence of generalized onset seizures. These seizures cause lapses in awareness, begin and end abruptly, typically last only a few seconds, and are associated with abnormal spike-wave discharges as seen by electroencephalogram.

Drug-induced hearing loss is a type of nonsyndromic deafness characterized by cochlear or vestibular dysfunction resulting in loss of hearing caused by drug ototoxicity. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with drug-induced hearing loss.

Oligoasthenoteratozoospermia is a type of male infertility, which is defined as a form of male infertility characterized by a combination of low number or oligozoospermia, poor motility or asthenozoospermia, and abnormal shape or teratozoospermia of sperms. It is the most common cause of male subfertility. Oligoasthenoteratozoospermia has exact synonyms: OAT and oligoasthenoteratospermia.
Thiamine deficiency disease is a type of nutritional deficiency disease, which is characterized by low levels of thiamine.

Obstructive nephropathy is a type of kidney disease characterized by kidney damage and dysfunction resulting from urinary tract obstruction. It is also exactly known as CON and congenital obstructive nephropathy.

Hypoplastic right heart syndrome is a type of congenital heart disease, which is characterized by the underdevelopment of the structures on the right side of the heart, and it is commonly associated with atrial septal defect. This condition also has the exact synonym "Right hypoplastic heart syndrome."

Miura type epiphyseal chondrodysplasia is an autosomal dominant disease and a type of bone development disorder that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a bone developmental disease characterized by tall stature, scoliosis, and macrodactyly of the great toes, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the NPR2 gene on chromosome 9p13. Furthermore, Miura type epiphyseal chondrodysplasia is exactly synonymous with ECDM, tall stature-scoliosis-macrodactyly of the great toes syndrome, and tall stature-scoliosis-macrodactyly of the halluces syndrome.

Wet beriberi is a type of beriberi that is characterized by being located in the cardiovascular system and exhibiting symptoms such as increased heart rate, swelling of the lower legs, and shortness of breath. Furthermore, this type of beriberi is associated with symptoms like tachycardia and dyspnea.

Dry beriberi is a type of beriberi that is specifically located in the nervous system. It is characterized by a range of symptoms including difficulty walking, numbness in extremities, tingling in extremities, paralysis of lower legs, difficulty speaking, confusion, and vomiting. Additionally, dry beriberi is associated with symptoms such as confusion, dysarthria, abnormality of gait, and vomiting, indicating a complex condition that affects various aspects of neurological function.
Miliaria pustulosa, a type of miliaria, is defined as a condition characterized by pustules resulting from inflammation and bacterial infection.

Miliaria profunda is a type of miliaria characterized by ductal occlusion of the papillary dermis. This condition causes the gland's secretions to leak between the superficial and deep layers of the skin, resulting in a rapidly-spreading flesh-colored rash.
Miliaria crystallina is a type of miliaria characterized by clear, superficial, noninflamed, subcorneal vesicles that easily rupture when rubbed. It is located in the stratum corneum.

Childhood hepatocellular carcinoma, which is also exactly known as pediatric hepatocellular carcinoma, is a type of hepatocellular carcinoma. It is defined as a hepatocellular carcinoma that occurs in children, characterized by a distinct etiological predisposition, biological behavior, and a lower frequency of cirrhosis compared to its adult counterpart. This type of carcinoma is something whose existence at least starts during some childhood onset.

Childhood acute myeloid leukemia is a type of leukemia that begins during childhood, also known as childhood onset. It is defined as a childhood leukemia characterized by the rapid growth of abnormal white blood cells that accumulate in the bone marrow and interfere with the production of normal blood cells. This condition is also precisely referred to by several synonyms, including childhood acute myeloid leukaemia, paediatric acute myeloid leukaemia, and pediatric acute myeloid leukemia.

Systemic Epstein Barr Virus positive T cell lymphoma of childhood is a type of childhood lymphoma and something that begins during childhood. It is defined as a childhood lymphoma characterized by the monoclonal expansion of Epstein-Barr virus-positive T cells with an activated cytotoxic phenotype in tissues or peripheral blood. Additionally, it has two exact synonyms: EBV-positive T-cell lymphoproliferative disorder of childhood and systemic EBV-positive T-cell lymphoma of childhood.

Malignant childhood adrenal gland pheochromocytoma is a specific type of adrenal gland pheochromocytoma that begins in childhood. It is defined as an adrenal gland pheochromocytoma characterized by rare chromaffin cell tumors that secrete catecholamines, with a higher prevalence of hereditary factors and metastasis in children than adults. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with malignant pediatric adrenal gland pheochromocytoma.

Spitzoid melanoma is a type of skin melanoma characterized by an asymmetric shape, a diameter greater than 1 cm, a lesion with a deep invasive component, and a high degree of cytologic atypia. It is also known by its exact synonym, atypical spitz nevus.

Melanoma in congenital melanocytic nevus is a type of skin melanoma, defined as a skin melanoma that arises from a congenital melanocytic nevus. It has exact synonyms, including "Malignant melanoma in congenital melanocytic nevus" and "melanocytic nevi."

Adult hepatocellular carcinoma is a type of hepatocellular carcinoma that starts during adult onset. It is associated with symptoms such as liver inflammation and abdominal mass. This condition is defined as a hepatocellular carcinoma characterized by hepatic mass, abdominal pain, and, in advanced stages, jaundice, cachexia, and liver failure, often developing in the setting of chronic necro-inflammation. Additionally, adult hepatocellular carcinoma is exactly synonymous with adult hepatoma and adult primary hepatocellular carcinoma.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome is a type of mitochondrial metabolism disease that is defined by a significant reduction in mitochondrial DNA in affected tissues, resulting in impaired mtDNA-encoded protein synthesis and energy production in the affected tissues and organs. It is also exactly synonymous with mtDNA depletion syndrome.

Multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome is a type of mitochondrial metabolism disease and has the definition of being a mitochondrial metabolism disease characterized by reduced function of more than one stage of energy production resulting from mitochondria impairment. It also has the exact synonym "fatal multiple mitochondrial dysfunction syndrome."

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 8B is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that inherently presents with autosomal recessive inheritance and exhibits phenotypes of gastrointestinal dysmotility and cachexia, along with symptoms such as ptosis. This syndrome is defined as a mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome characterized by ophthalmoplegia, ptosis, gastrointestinal dysmotility, cachexia, peripheral neuropathy, and brain MRI changes, collectively known as the MNGIE phenotype. It has its material basis in autosomal recessive homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ribonucleotide reductase M2 B gene located on chromosome 8q22. Additionally, mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 8B is exactly synonymous with mitochondrial neurogastrointestinal encephalopathy syndrome, RRM2B-related.

Multiple Mitochondrial Dysfunctions Syndrome 6 (MMDS6) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also a category of Multiple Mitochondrial Dysfunctions Syndrome. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by symptoms including hypotonia, an inability to walk, poor speech, intellectual disability, and various motor abnormalities like ataxia, dystonia, and spasticity. These symptoms typically begin in early childhood. The material basis for MMDS6 is traced to autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically through homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PMPCB gene located on chromosome 7q22.
Breast implant-associated anaplastic large cell lymphoma is a type of peripheral T-cell lymphoma characterized by development around textured-surface breast implants confined to the capsule.

Vegetable allergy is a type of food allergy and is also a type of something that has at least one allergic trigger from some vegetable food product. Furthermore, it is defined as a food allergy triggered by a vegetable food product.

A celery allergy is a type of vegetable allergy and also falls under the category of things that have an allergic trigger, specifically some leaf celery food products. It is defined as a vegetable allergy triggered by celery (Apium graveolens).

Arthrogryposis multiplex congenita 6 is a type of arthrogryposis multiplex congenita, which begins during congenital onset. It is characterized by congenital joint contractures, dysmorphic facial features, distal skeletal anomalies with clenched hands and clubfeet, and edema with fetal hydrops. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NEB gene on chromosome 2q23.

Epithelial recurrent erosion dystrophy (ERED) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which is also classified as an epithelial and subepithelial dystrophy. It originates from autosomal dominant inheritance. ERED is defined as an epithelial and subepithelial dystrophy that is characterized by frequent painful recurrent corneal erosions, small gray anterior stromal flecks associated with larger focal gray-white disc-shaped, circular, or wreath-like lesions with central clarity. Additionally, ERED has the exact synonyms COL17A1 and ERED.

Cerebellar hypoplasia is a specific type of cerebellar disease characterized by a cerebellum that is smaller than usual or not completely developed. Additionally, it has an exact match with the MESH identifier C562568.

Cerebellar hypoplasia, atrophy, epilepsy, and global developmental delay constitute a syndrome characterized by several key features. This syndrome, which has a cerebellar malformation as a major feature, is marked by cerebellar hypoplasia, bilateral retinal pigmentary changes, and intellectual disability that can range from mild to moderate, along with a pronounced language development delay. It presents with early developmental delay, central and peripheral non-progressive visual impairment or asymptomatic retinal changes, hypotonia, non-progressive ataxia, and nystagmus. Additionally, this syndrome is identified as having at least one symptom of nystagmus and at least one disease feature of intellectual disability.

Classic citrullinemia is a type of citrullinemia characterized by a condition that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ASS1 gene, which encodes argininosuccinate synthetase, located on chromosome 9q34.

Neonatal onset type II citrullinemia is a type of citrullinemia and an autosomal recessive disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a citrullinemia that is characterized by confusion, restlessness, memory loss, abnormal behaviors such as aggression, irritability, and hyperactivity, seizures, and coma, caused by citrin deficiency (NICCD), and has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC25A13 gene. Additionally, neonatal onset type II citrullinemia has an exact synonym: neonatal-onset type 2 citrullinemia.

Adult onset type II citrullinemia is a type of citrullinemia and also a condition that begins in adulthood. It is defined as a citrullinemia that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SLC25A13 gene located on chromosome 7q21. Furthermore, adult onset type II citrullinemia is exactly synonymous with citrin deficiency.

CSF1R-related brain malformation and osteopetrosis is a type of neuroaxonal dystrophy, which is defined as a neuroaxonal dystrophy that has its material basis in heterozygous mutations in CSF1R. This condition causes adult-onset leukoencephalopathy with axonal spheroids and pigmented glia, characterized by progressive cognitive and motor impairment and seizures in the fourth to fifth decade of life. Moreover, it has the exact synonym osteoporosis and infantile neuroaxonal dystrophy.

Ocular tuberculosis is a type of tuberculosis, an eye disease, and a condition that has its location in some part of the eye. It is defined as tuberculosis that is located in the eye, has its material basis in Mycobacterium tuberculosis, and has symptoms including inflamed eyes.

Vertebral anomalies and variable endocrine and T cell dysfunction is a syndrome and a type of autosomal dominant disease that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome with a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the TBX2 gene on chromosome 17q23, characterized by craniofacial dysmorphisms, cardiac anomalies, skeletal malformations, immune deficiency, endocrine abnormalities, and developmental impairments. Additionally, it has the exact synonym "heterozygotes for TBX2 variants."

The neurodevelopmental disorder with cataracts, poor growth, and dysmorphic facies is a type of syndrome that falls into a category of conditions sharing at least one phenotype of neurodevelopmental abnormality and at least one symptom of abnormality of gait. This same disorder is also recognized as a type of disease that notably features cataracts. Additionally, it is defined as a syndrome characterized by impaired intellectual development with absent language and short stature, which has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the INTS1 gene on chromosome 7p22.

Encephalopathy due to defective mitochondrial and peroxisomal fission 1 is a type of syndrome and something that at least has the symptom of some delayed psychomotor development. It is defined as a syndrome that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the DNM1L gene. This condition is characterized by delayed psychomotor development and has the symptom of hypotonia, which may lead to death in childhood.

Spinal muscular atrophy with lower extremity predominant is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of spinal muscular atrophy. It is a condition that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is characterized by symptoms such as muscle weakness. Specifically, it is a spinal muscular atrophy that has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is characterized by muscle weakness and wasting in the lower limbs, most notably affecting the thigh muscles. Additionally, spinal muscular atrophy with lower extremity predominant is exactly synonymous with spinal muscular atrophy with lower extremity predominance.

Spinal Muscular Atrophy with Lower Extremity Predominant 2A (SMA-LEP 2A) is a specific subtype of Spinal Muscular Atrophy with Lower Extremity Predominant. This condition is characterized by muscle weakness and atrophy, primarily affecting the proximal and distal muscles of the lower extremity, with possible involvement of upper extremity muscles in some patients. It typically begins in early childhood. The underlying cause of SMA-LEP 2A is a heterozygous mutation in the BICD2 gene located on chromosome 9q22. Additionally, this disorder is associated with autosomal dominant inheritance and has muscle weakness as one of its symptoms. SMA-LEP 2A is also precisely known as Spinal Muscular Atrophy with Lower Extremity Predominance 2A.

Spinal muscular atrophy with lower extremity predominant 2b (SMA-LE 2b) is a specific type of spinal muscular atrophy characterized by lower extremity predominance. It is also known as spinal muscular atrophy with lower extremity predominance 2B, indicating its exact synonym. This condition is part of a group that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, indicating a genetic component. SMA-LE 2b is defined by its distinct characteristics, including decreased fetal movements and congenital contractures consistent with arthrogryposis multiplex congenita. These manifestations are due to a heterozygous mutation in the BICD2 gene located on chromosome 9q22.

Spinal muscular atrophy with lower extremity predominant 1 is a specific type of spinal muscular atrophy characterized by a predominance in the lower extremities. This condition falls under the category of disorders that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined by a spinal muscular atrophy with lower extremity predominance that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the DYNC1H1 gene located on chromosome 14q32. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with spinal muscular atrophy with lower extremity predominance 1.

Stress-induced childhood onset neurodegeneration with variable ataxia and seizures (CONDSIAS) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and neurodegenerative disease. It is characterized by its basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance and starts its existence during childhood. The disease has symptoms including ataxia, muscle weakness, and seizures. Specifically, CONDSIAS is defined as a neurodegenerative disease characterized by variable ataxia and seizures, with its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the ADPRHL2 gene on chromosome 1p34. This condition also presents symptoms such as seizures, muscle weakness, gait ataxia, impaired speech, hearing loss, and cerebellar atrophy.

Cataract 47 is a type of cataract and an autosomal dominant disease, which specifically has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a cataract that results from a heterozygous mutation in the SLC16A12 gene on chromosome 10q23, and is characterized by progressive juvenile cataract with microcornea. Additionally, Cataract 47 has the exact synonym CTRCT47.

Cataract 48 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of cataract, which essentially has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a cataract that originates from a homozygous mutation in the DNMBP gene on chromosome 10q24, characterized by infantile or early-childhood cataracts and visual impairment. Furthermore, it has the exact synonym CTRCT48.

Overactive bladder syndrome is a type of syndrome, disease, and something that at least has the symptom of urinary urgency, as well as being a condition where the disease has its basis in some symptom. It is defined as a bladder disease characterized by urinary urgency without urinary tract infection or obvious pathology, usually accompanied by urinary frequency and nocturia. Additionally, overactive bladder syndrome has exact synonyms such as OAB, overactive bladder, urge syndrome, and urgency-frequency syndrome.

Visual impairment and progressive phthisis bulbi is a type of autosomal recessive disease, eye disease, and something that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an eye disease characterized by poor vision at birth, with the development of bilateral phthisis by adulthood, and it has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the MARK3 gene on chromosome 14q32.

Nephrotic syndrome type 20 is a type of familial nephrotic syndrome defined as a familial nephrotic syndrome that has a material basis in an X-linked renal disorder. This disorder is characterized by the onset of steroid-resistant nephrotic syndrome and proteinuria in the first years of life in affected males.

Primary biliary cholangitis 1 is a type of primary biliary cholangitis defined as having a material basis in variation at the IL12A locus on chromosome 3q25.33. It is exactly synonymous with BILIARY CIRRHOSIS, PRIMARY, 1, and also known as PBC1.

Primary Biliary Cholangitis 2 is a type of Primary Biliary Cholangitis, which is defined as a Primary Biliary Cholangitis that has a material basis in variation at the HLA-DQB1 locus on chromosome 6p21.3. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms including BILIARY CIRRHOSIS, PRIMARY, 2, and PBC2.

Primary biliary cholangitis 3 is a type of primary biliary cholangitis that is defined by a primary biliary cholangitis with a material basis in variation at the IL12RB2 locus on chromosome 1p31.2. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms BILIARY CIRRHOSIS, PRIMARY, 3, and PBC3.

Primary Biliary Cholangitis 4 is a type of Primary Biliary Cholangitis that is defined by a variation near the IRF5-TNPO3 locus on chromosome 7q32. It is also exactly synonymous with Biliary Cirrhosis, Primary, 4, and PBC4.

Primary biliary cholangitis 5 is a type of primary biliary cholangitis that is defined as a primary biliary cholangitis with a material basis in variation at the ZPBP2 locus on chromosome 17q12-q21. It is also exactly synonymous with BILIARY CIRRHOSIS, PRIMARY, 5 and PBC5.

Bradyopsia 1 is a type of bradyopsia, which is characterized by a condition that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RGS9 gene on chromosome 17q24. It is exactly synonymous with prolonged electroretinal response suppression 1 and has an exact match with OMIM:608415.

Bradyopsia 2 is a type of bradyopsia, which is defined as a bradyopsia that has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the RGS9BP gene located on chromosome 19q13. Furthermore, it has an exact synonym, prolonged electroretinal response suppression 2, and an exact match with OMIM:620344.

Nevoid basal cell carcinoma syndrome 1, also precisely known as basal cell nevus syndrome 1 and matched exactly with OMIM:109400, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of nevoid basal cell carcinoma syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. This particular syndrome is defined by a nevoid basal cell carcinoma syndrome that arises due to a heterozygous mutation in the PTCH1 gene located on chromosome 9q22.

Nevoid Basal Cell Carcinoma Syndrome 2 is a type of Nevoid Basal Cell Carcinoma Syndrome and has the exact synonym Basal Cell Nevus Syndrome 2. It is defined as a Nevoid Basal Cell Carcinoma Syndrome that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SUFU gene located on chromosome 10q24. Furthermore, Nevoid Basal Cell Carcinoma Syndrome 2 has an exact match with OMIM:620343.

Leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter 5 is a specific type of leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter. It is defined as a leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter characterized by a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the EIF2B5 gene located on chromosome 3q27. This condition is also precisely known as Cree leukoencephalopathy. Furthermore, it has exact matches with OMIM:620315 and ORDO:99854.

Autosomal recessive chronic granulomatous disease 5 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, a type of chronic granulomatous disease, and also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a chronic granulomatous disease characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, which has its material basis in a mutation in the CYBC1 gene on chromosome 17q25.

Restrictive dermopathy 1 is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of restrictive dermopathy, indicating it stems from a condition that inherently involves autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a restrictive dermopathy that arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ZMPSTE24 gene located on chromosome 1p34. Additionally, restrictive dermopathy 1 is precisely identified by the OMIM code 275210.

Restrictive dermopathy 2 is a type of restrictive dermopathy, which is defined as a restrictive dermopathy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the LMNA gene on chromosome 1q22. Additionally, it has an exact match with OMIM:619793.

Leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter 4 is a type of leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter, which is defined as a leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter that has a material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the EIF2B4 gene on chromosome 2p23. Additionally, it has an exact match with OMIM:620314.

Leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter 3 is a type of leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter, characterized by a definition that specifies it as a leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter with a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the EIF2B3 gene on chromosome 1p34. Additionally, Leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter 3 has an exact match with OMIM:620313.

Leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter 2 is a specific type of leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter. It is defined as a leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter that occurs due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the EIF2B2 gene located on chromosome 14q24. Furthermore, leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter 2 exactly matches with the OMIM identifier 620312.

Leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter 1 is a specific type of leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter, characterized by a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the EIF2B1 gene located on chromosome 12q24. Furthermore, it exactly matches the reference OMIM:603896.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 64 (DEE64), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 64, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. This condition is specifically classified as an autosomal dominant disease with its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. DEE64 is characterized by a variety of severe symptoms, including the infantile onset of seizures, profound intellectual disabilities, impaired motor functions, movement disorders, and postnatal microcephaly. The underlying cause of DEE64 is a heterozygous mutation in the RHOBTB2 gene located on chromosome 8p21.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 31b (DEE31B) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is specifically classified under developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. This condition is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 31b details it as a disorder marked by early-onset epilepsy, generalized muscular hypotonia, visual impairment, and severe neurodevelopmental delay. This condition arises from a homozygous mutation in the DNM1 gene located on chromosome 9q34.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 96 (DEE96) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. This classification stems from its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. DEE96 is characterized by the onset of seizures in the first days or weeks of life, due to a heterozygous mutation in the NSF gene located on chromosome 17q21.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 109 (DEE109) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific kind of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is characterized by the onset of various types of seizures in the first months or years of life, which stems from a heterozygous mutation in the FZR1 gene on chromosome 19p13. This condition is also understood to have a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 6b (DEE6B) is a type of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy, as well as a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a specific type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. DEE6B is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by early-infantile seizure onset, profoundly impaired intellectual development, and a hyperkinetic movement disorder. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SCN1A gene located on chromosome 2q24. Moreover, this disease shares the same genetic basis as Dravet syndrome (DOID:0080422) but is considered more severe.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 85 (DEE85), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 85, is a type of X-linked dominant disease and falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. It is characterized by severe refractory seizures that begin in the first year of life, global developmental delay with impaired intellectual development, poor or absent speech, and dysmorphic facial features. These manifestations are due to a heterozygous mutation in the SMC1A gene located on chromosome Xp11. Furthermore, DEE85 is associated with a condition that essentially has a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 90 (DEE90) is a type of X-linked monogenic disease and a specific form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance. Specifically, DEE90 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by the onset of refractory seizures in the first days or months of life, which has its material basis in either hemizygous or heterozygous mutation in the FGF13 gene located on chromosome Xq26.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 95 (DEE95), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 95, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. This condition is defined by severely impaired global development, hypotonia, weakness, ataxia, coarse facial features, and intractable seizures. Its material basis is linked to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PIGS gene located on chromosome 17q11, indicating that it at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 97 (DEE97), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 97, is classified as a type of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy and an autosomal dominant disease. It specifically involves a condition that fundamentally requires at least some material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. DEE97 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that is characterized by the onset of seizures within the first few months of life, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the CELF2 gene located on chromosome 10p14.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 98 (DEE98), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 98, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized as a condition that essentially has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, DEE98 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by the onset of seizures within the first decade of life, which is associated with variable global developmental delays. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ATP1A2 gene located on chromosome 1q23.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 99 (DEE99), also known exactly as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 99, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. This condition is characterized as something that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that begins with the onset of seizures in early childhood, which results from a heterozygous mutation in the ATP1A3 gene located on chromosome 19q13.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 100 (DEE100), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 100, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. This condition is characterized by the onset of various types of seizures in the first months or years of life, preceded by global developmental delay. The underlying cause is a heterozygous mutation in the FBXO28 gene located on chromosome 1q42. Additionally, developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 100 has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 101 (DEE101), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 101, is a type of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease and is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by early infantile epileptic encephalopathy and severe global developmental delay. This condition has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the GRIN1 gene located on chromosome 9q34, indicating that it is a result of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 102 (DEE102), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 102, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, DEE102 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy marked by global developmental delay and severe to profoundly impaired intellectual development, with affected individuals unable to walk or speak. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SLC38A3 gene located on chromosome 3p21.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 103 (DEE103), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 103, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific instance of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. This condition is characterized by the onset of various types of seizures within the first year of life, which is attributed to a heterozygous mutation in the KCNC2 gene on chromosome 12q21. The disease falls under the category of disorders with a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 104 (DEE104), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 104, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is characterized by a type of condition that essentially has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, DEE104 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy marked by developmental delay in the initial months of life and drug-resistant focal and generalized tonic-clonic seizures. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ATP6V0A1 gene located on chromosome 17q21.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 105 (DEE105), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 105, is a type of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that essentially requires a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, DEE105 is defined by the onset of seizures and pituitary insufficiency within the first weeks or months of life, accompanied by profoundly impaired development. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the HID1 gene located on chromosome 17q25.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 106 (DEE106), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 106, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. It is characterized by a condition that essentially has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, DEE106 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy marked by the onset of various types of frequent seizures within the first year of life and profound global developmental delay, including limited mobility and absent speech. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the UFSP2 gene located on chromosome 4q35.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 107 (DEE107), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 107, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is a condition that arises from autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically due to a homozygous mutation in the NAPB gene located on chromosome 20p11. This encephalopathy is characterized by the onset of seizures within the first months of life, severe global developmental delay, profound intellectual disability, progressive microcephaly, and hypotonia.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 108 (DEE108), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 108, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. This condition is characterized by the onset of multiple types of seizures within the first two years of life, attributed to a heterozygous mutation in the MAST3 gene on chromosome 19p13. It is also associated with autosomal dominant inheritance, emphasizing its genetic basis.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 110 (DEE110), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 110, is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. This condition is characterized by a profound global developmental delay and hypotonia noticeable in infancy, followed by the onset of seizures in the first months or years of life. The disease has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CACNA2D1 gene located on chromosome 7q21, which underscores its genetic foundation in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Progressive leukoencephalopathy with ovarian failure is a type of autosomal recessive disease and leukodystrophy, which fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by a loss of motor and cognitive skills, typically beginning in young adulthood, and is caused by compound heterozygous mutation in the AARS2 gene located on chromosome 6p21. This condition is also known by its synonym, ovarioleukodystrophy. Furthermore, it has an exact match with OMIM:615889 and a related match with ORDO:99853.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 23 (HLD23) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy, which inherently has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by ataxia, deafness, liver dysfunction, and dilated cardiomyopathy due to a homozygous mutation in the RNF220 gene on chromosome 1p34, leading to death in the first or second decade of life.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 15 (HLD15) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy, which essentially has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy characterized by the onset of motor and cognitive impairment of variable severity in the first or second decade of life. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the EPRS1 gene located on chromosome 1q41.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 18 (HLD18) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of HLD18 is a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy characterized by the onset of global developmental delay in infancy or early childhood, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DEGS1 gene on chromosome 1q42.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 19 (HLD19) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy, which inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy characterized by the onset of transient neurologic abnormalities in early infancy, with these symptoms resolving within the first or second decades. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the TMEM63A gene located on chromosome 1q42.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 25 (HLD25) is a type of autosomal dominant disease which falls under the broader category of hypomyelinating leukodystrophies. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, HLD25 is defined as a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy marked by horizontal nystagmus, hypotonia, and global developmental delay that become apparent soon after birth or during infancy. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the TMEM163 gene located on chromosome 2q21.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 22 (HLD22) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by a global developmental delay with mildly impaired intellectual development, motor impairment leading to limited or no ability to walk, and dysarthria. This condition is specifically caused by a heterozygous mutation in the CLDN11 gene located on chromosome 3q26.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 26 (HLD26) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific kind of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy. It is categorized as a condition that fundamentally results from some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. HLD26 is defined as a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy that is characterized by severe psychomotor delay, predominantly affecting motor and expressive language development, alongside cerebral and cerebellar atrophy, and corpus callosum hypoplasia. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the SLC35B2 gene located on chromosome 6p21.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 17 (HLD17) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically categorized under hypomyelinating leukodystrophies. It is defined by its onset in early infancy, characterized by microcephaly and lack of overall development, which has its material basis in homozygous mutations in the AIMP2 gene located on chromosome 7p22. This condition is also a type of disorder that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 16 (HLD16) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy, which fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy characterized by the onset of hypotonia, nystagmus, and mildly delayed motor development in infancy, arising from a heterozygous mutation in the TMEM106B gene located on chromosome 7p21.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 24, also known exactly as HLD24, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy. It is defined as a hypomyelinating leukodystrophy characterized by a global developmental delay and neurologic deterioration that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ATP11A gene on chromosome 13q34. This condition is also described as something that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Hypomyelinating leukodystrophy 21 (HLD21) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a variant of hypomyelinating leukodystrophy. This condition is rooted in autosomal recessive inheritance and is specifically characterized by global developmental delays noticeable from infancy, including the loss of motor, speech, and cognitive milestones in the first decades of life. The underlying cause is a homozygous mutation in the POLR3K gene located on chromosome 16p13.

Hengel Maroofian Schols Syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which inherently has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by infant or early childhood onset, impaired intellectual development with poor or absent speech, pyramidal signs, microcephaly, short stature, and dysmorphic facial features, with its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the BCAS3 gene on chromosome 17q23. Moreover, it has an exact match with OMIM:619641.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 28 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia and has the exact synonym SCAR28. It is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by onset in early childhood of mildly delayed motor development, gait ataxia, incoordination of fine motor movements, and dysarthria. This condition has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the THG1L gene on chromosome 5q33.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 29 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which is precisely defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by delayed motor development in early infancy, followed by difficulty walking due to an ataxic gait or inability to walk, hypotonia, and variably impaired intellectual development. The condition's material basis lies in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the VPS41 gene on chromosome 7p14. Additionally, it has the exact synonym SCAR29.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 30, which is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia and has the exact synonym SCAR30, is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by childhood-onset global developmental delay with variably impaired intellectual development, motor dysfunction, and cerebellar ataxia. This condition has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the PITRM1 gene on chromosome 10p15.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 31 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by global developmental delay with hypotonia and variably impaired intellectual and language development. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ATG7 gene on chromosome 3p25. Additionally, autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 31 has an exact synonym: SCAR31.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 32, which has the exact synonym SCAR32, is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia. It is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by the onset of gait ataxia in the second or third decade of life, which has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PRDX3 gene on chromosome 10q26.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 33 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, and it is exactly synonymous with SCAR33. It is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by delayed motor development apparent in infancy, unsteady ataxic gait, intention tremor, nystagmus, and speech delay with dysarthria. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the RNU12 gene on chromosome 22q13.

Brachycephaly trichomegaly and developmental delay (BTDD), also known exactly as MCINS or Macinnes syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome. It is a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, BTDD is defined as a syndrome characterized by brachycephaly, trichomegaly, and developmental delay, without anemia, and it has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the RPS23 gene on chromosome 5q14.

Luo Schoch Yamamoto Syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder, which is further defined as an autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder characterized by global developmental delay and impaired intellectual development apparent from infancy. This disorder has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the RNF2 gene on chromosome 1q25. Additionally, Luo Schoch Yamamoto Syndrome has an exact synonym, LUSYAM.

Neurodevelopmental disorder with speech impairment and dysmorphic facies is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder, which is precisely defined as an autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder characterized by developmental delay associated with mild to moderately impaired intellectual development or learning difficulties, behavioral or psychiatric abnormalities, and delayed speech and language acquisition. This disorder has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SETD1A gene on chromosome 16p11. Additionally, it has the exact synonym NEDSID.

Vertebral hypersegmentation and orofacial anomalies is a syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases and is also considered as something that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by the presence of supernumerary (additional) cervical, thoracic, and/or lumbar vertebrae, often accompanied by supernumerary ribs, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the GDF11 gene located on chromosome 12q13. Additionally, vertebral hypersegmentation and orofacial anomalies are exactly synonymous with VHO.

Acrocardiofacial syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by a combination of features including split-hand/split-foot malformation, facial anomalies, cleft lip/palate, congenital heart defect, genital anomalies, and intellectual deficit. It is also known by its exact synonyms: cleft palate, cardiac defect, genital anomalies, and ectrodactyly, as well as cleft palate-cardiac defect-genital anomalies-ectrodactyly syndrome.

Developmental delay, hypotonia, and impaired language is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder. It is defined as an autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder characterized by variably impaired intellectual development, usually with hypotonia, mild motor delay, and language difficulties, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FBXW7 gene on chromosome 4q31. Furthermore, it has the exact synonym DEDHIL.

The neurodevelopmental disorder with spasticity and poor growth is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder. It is defined as an autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder characterized by axial hypotonia, delayed psychomotor development, poor feeding, and failure to thrive with onset in early infancy, which has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the UFC1 gene on chromosome 1q23. Furthermore, this disorder is exactly synonymous with NEDSG.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, Pilorge type, is a specific kind of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by global developmental delay with variably impaired intellectual development, speech delay, and behavioral abnormalities including autism spectrum disorder, which arises from a heterozygous or hemizygous mutation in the GLRA2 gene on chromosome Xp22. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with MRXSP.

Early onset progressive encephalopathy with brain atrophy and thin corpus callosum is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder also known by its exact synonyms PEBAT and early-onset progressive encephalopathy with brain atrophy and thin corpus callosum. This disorder is characterized by onset at birth or in infancy of developmental delay, intellectual disability, seizures, secondary hypomyelination, cerebral atrophy, and thin corpus callosum. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TBCD gene on chromosome 17q25.

Combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency 44 (COXPD44) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and is also categorized under combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is characterized by a condition that essentially has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of COXPD44 includes being a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FASTKD2 gene located on chromosome 2q33. Furthermore, COXPD44 is precisely identified in medical databases with the exact match identifiers OMIM:618855 and ORDO:166105.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 52 (COXPD52) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that falls under the category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is characterized by conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, COXPD52 is defined by an infantile onset, lactic acidemia, hypotonia, respiratory chain complex II and III deficiency, and multisystem organ failure, which are due to a homozygous mutation in the NFS1 gene located on chromosome 20q11. Additionally, COXPD52 has an exact match in the OMIM database with the identifier OMIM:619386.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 53 (COXPD53), which has an exact match in the OMIM database with the entry 619423, is categorized as a type of Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency and is also recognized as a form of autosomal recessive disease. This classification is based on its nature of having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, COXPD53 is defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that is characterized by congenital-to-infantile onset, hypomyelination, microcephaly, liver dysfunction, and recurrent autoinflammation. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the C2ORF69 gene located on chromosome 2q33.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 54 (COXPD54) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is defined by a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that originates from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PRORP gene located on chromosome 14q13. Additionally, COXPD54 is precisely matched with the OMIM identifier 619737.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 55 (COXPD55) is a type of autosomal genetic disease and a specific form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency, which inherently has a material basis in autosomal inheritance. It is defined as a combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency that arises due to homozygous, compound heterozygous, or heterozygous mutation in the POLRMT gene located on chromosome 19p13. Additionally, COXPD55 is precisely matched with the OMIM identifier 619743.

Combined Oxidative Phosphorylation Deficiency 56 (COXPD56) is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. It is identified by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. COXPD56 is characterized by a range of symptoms including lethargy at birth, hypotonia, developmental delay, myopathy, and ptosis, all of which are due to compound heterozygous mutations in the TAMM41 gene located on chromosome 3p25. Additionally, COXPD56 is exactly matched with the OMIM entry number 620139.

Combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency 57 (COXPD57), which has an exact match with OMIM:620167, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency. It is characterized by having its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically through compound heterozygous or homozygous mutations in the CRLS1 gene located on chromosome 20p12.

Hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder characterized by hyperphosphatasia and intellectual disability. This condition often presents with distinctive facial features, including hypertelorism, long palpebral fissures, a broad bridge and rounded tip of the nose, downturned corners of the mouth, and a thin upper lip. It is exactly synonymous with HPMRS, Mabry disease, Mabry syndrome, and hyperphosphatasia with mental retardation syndrome. Additionally, it has exact matches with OMIM:PS239300, ORDO:247262, and UMLS_CUI:C1855923.

Hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome 5 is a specific type of hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome. It is defined as a hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome that originates from a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PIGW gene located on chromosome 17q12. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms including GPIBD11, HPMRS5, glycosylphosphatidylinositol biosynthesis defect 11, and hyperphosphatasia with mental retardation syndrome 5. Additionally, it has an exact match with OMIM identifier 616025.

Hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome 1 is a specific type within the broader category of hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome. It is characterized by a material basis involving either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PIGV gene located on chromosome 1p36. This condition is also precisely identified by several exact synonyms: GPIBD2, HPMRS1, glycosylphosphatidylinositol biosynthesis defect 2, and hyperphosphatasia with mental retardation syndrome 1. Furthermore, it perfectly matches the entries OMIM:239300 and UMLS_CUI:C4551502 in medical databases.

Hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome 2 is a specific type of hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome. This syndrome is defined by a hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development that has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutations in the PIGO gene located on chromosome 9p13. It is also known by several exact synonyms including GPIBD6, HPMRS2, glycosylphosphatidylinositol biosynthesis defect 6, and hyperphosphatasia with mental retardation syndrome 2. Additionally, it has an exact match with the OMIM database entry 614749.

Hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome 3 is a specific type within the broader category of hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that arises from either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PGAP2 gene located on chromosome 11p15. This syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms including GPIBD8, HPMRS3, glycosylphosphatidylinositol biosynthesis defect 8, and hyperphosphatasia with mental retardation syndrome 3. Moreover, it has an exact match in the OMIM database with the identifier 614207.

Hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome 4 is a specific type within the broader category of hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome. It is characterized by a hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome that originates from either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PGAP3 gene located on chromosome 17q12. This syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms including GPIBD62, HPMRS6, glycosylphosphatidylinositol biosynthesis defect 62, and hyperphosphatasia with mental retardation syndrome 6. Additionally, it precisely matches with the OMIM identifier 615716.

Hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome 6 is a specific type of hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome. It is defined by a hyperphosphatasia with impaired intellectual development syndrome that arises from a homozygous mutation in the PIGY gene located on chromosome 4q22. This condition is precisely matched with OMIM identifier 616809 and is exactly synonymous with several terms including GPIBD40, HPMRS4, glycosylphosphatidylinositol biosynthesis defect 40, and hyperphosphatasia with mental retardation syndrome 4.

Retinal macular dystrophy is a type of autosomal dominant disease and macular degeneration, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by non-progression or slow progression and drusen-like deposits in varying degrees. Furthermore, retinal macular dystrophy has the exact synonym MCDR and an exact match with OMIM:PS136550.

@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:north_carolina_macular_dystrophy rdfs:subClassOf :retinal_macular_dystrophy ;
    :has_definition "A retinal macular dystrophy characterized by limited drusen, larger confluent drusen, or severe colobomatous-like chorioretinal atrophy in the central macular region present at birth that are nonprogressive that has_material_basis_in heterozygous mutation in a DNase I hypersensitivity site on chromosome 6q16 upstream of the PRDM13 gene." ;
    :has_exact_match "GARD:9179",
        "MESH:C537835",
        "OMIM:136550",
        "ORDO:75327",
        "UMLS_CUI:C0730294" ;
    :has_exact_synonym "MCDR1",
        "NCMD",
        "central areolar pigment epithelial dystrophy",
        "central retinal pigment epithelial dystrophy",
        "progressive foveal dystrophy",
        "retinal macular dystrophy 1" .
text: North Carolina macular dystrophy is a type of retinal macular dystrophy characterized by limited drusen, larger confluent drusen, or severe colobomatous-like chorioretinal atrophy in the central macular region present at birth that are nonprogressive. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in a DNase I hypersensitivity site on chromosome 6q16 upstream of the PRDM13 gene. It is also known by several exact synonyms: MCDR1, NCMD, central areolar pigment epithelial dystrophy, central retinal pigment epithelial dystrophy, progressive foveal dystrophy, and retinal macular dystrophy 1. Furthermore, North Carolina macular dystrophy is matched exactly with several databases and identifiers, including GARD:9179, MESH:C537835, OMIM:136550, ORDO:75327, and UMLS_CUI:C0730294.

Retinal macular dystrophy 3 is a type of retinal macular dystrophy characterized by a variation in the chromosomal region 5p15.33-p13.1. It is also known by its exact synonym, MCDR3. Furthermore, retinal macular dystrophy 3 has an exact match with OMIM:608850.

Retinal macular dystrophy 4 is a type of retinal macular dystrophy, characterized by late-onset macular degeneration that includes multiple drusen-like deposits, macular geographic atrophy, and choroidal neovascularization. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CLEC3B gene located on chromosome 3p21. Additionally, retinal macular dystrophy 4 is precisely synonymous with MCDR4 and has an exact match with the OMIM identifier 619977.

Paroxysmal nonkinesigenic dyskinesia 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, dystonia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a dystonia characterized by epilepsy and attacks of dystonic or choreathetotic movements, which may coexist or occur singly, and has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KCNMA1 gene on chromosome 10q22. Additionally, it has the exact synonym "generalized epilepsy and paroxysmal dyskinesia" and matches exactly with OMIM:609446 and ORDO:79137.

Neurodevelopmental disorder with cerebellar atrophy and motor dysfunction is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder characterized by cerebellar atrophy and global developmental delay accompanied by cognitive impairment, speech delay, and notable motor abnormalities including axial hypotonia, gait ataxia, and appendicular spasticity. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GEMIN5 gene located on chromosome 5q33.2. Additionally, it is precisely matched to OMIM:619333.

Neurodevelopmental disorder with language delay and seizures is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder, which is characterized by early-onset seizures and global developmental delay with intellectual disability and speech delay. This disorder has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TIAM1 gene on chromosome 21q22. Additionally, it has an exact match with OMIM:619908.

Early onset dystonia and or spastic paraplegia is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease, dystonia, and something that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a dystonia characterized by a variable onset of dystonia, spasticity, or both, which has its material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ATP5MC3 gene on chromosome 2q31.1. Moreover, it has an exact match with OMIM:619681.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 16 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically a subtype of mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome, and it inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome characterized by the infantile onset of fulminant hepatic liver failure, which results from a homozygous mutation in the POLG2 gene located on chromosome 17q23.3. Additionally, mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 16 is exactly synonymous with mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 16 (hepatic type) and has an exact match with the identifier OMIM:618528.
